<h3>Binary to Decimal</h3>

<ol>
	<li>Number the digits starting from 0 and going to the right. The leftmost digit should end up as (number of digits) - 1 <br>

		ex. 10110010

		<table>
			<tr>
				<td></td>
				<td>1</td>
				<td>0</td>
				<td>1</td>
				<td>1</td>
				<td>0</td>
				<td>0</td>
				<td>1</td>
				<td>0</td>
			</tr>
			<tr>
				<td>digit number</td>
				<td>7</td>
				<td>6</td>
				<td>5</td>
				<td>4</td>
				<td>3</td>
				<td>2</td>
				<td>1</td>
				<td>0</td>
			</tr>
		</table>
	</li> <br>

	<li>Multiply each bit by 2^(its digit number) <br>

		<table>
			<tr>
				<td>ex. </td>
				<td>(1 x 2^7) = 128</td>
			</tr>
			<tr>
				<td></td>
				<td>(0 x 2^6) = 0</td>
			<tr>
			<tr>
				<td></td>
				<td>(1 x 2^5) = 32</td>
			<tr>
			<tr>
				<td></td>
				<td>(1 x 2^4) = 16</td>
			<tr>
			<tr>
				<td></td>
				<td>(0 x 2^3) = 0</td>
			<tr>
			<tr>
				<td></td>
				<td>(0 x 2^2) = 0</td>
			<tr>
			<tr>
				<td></td>
				<td>(1 x 2^1) = 2</td>
			<tr>
			<tr>
				<td></td>
				<td>(0 x 2^0) = 0</td>
			<tr>
		</table>
	</li> <br>

	<li>Sum the results from the last step. This is the decimal form of the original binary number! <br>

	ex. 128 + 0 + 32 + 16 + 0 + 0 + 2 + 0 = 178</li>
</ol>

<h3>Decimal to Binary</h3>

<ol>
	<li>Repeatedly divide the decimal number by 2 until the quotient is 0, keeping track of the remainder each time. <br>

		<table>
			<tr>
				<td>ex. </td>
				<td>42 / 2 = 21 R <b>0</b></td>
			</tr>
			<tr>
				<td></td>
				<td>21 / 2 = 10 R <b>1</b></td>
			<tr>
			<tr>
				<td></td>
				<td>10 / 2 = 5 R <b>0</b></td>
			<tr>
			<tr>
				<td></td>
				<td>5 / 2 = 2 R <b>1</b></td>
			<tr>
			<tr>
				<td></td>
				<td>2 / 2 = 1 R <b>0</b></td>
			<tr>
			<tr>
				<td></td>
				<td>1 / 2 = 0 R <b>1</b></td>
			<tr>
		</table>
	</li> <br>

	<li>Append the remainders, with the remainder from the last division as the leftmost bit and the remainder from the first division as the rightmost bit. This is your binary value.<br>

		ex. 101110</li>
</ol>

